- "stewards" refers to the managers in charge of the departments;
- "largest annual budgets" means the highest budgets allocated to the departments;
- The ranking is done in descending order of the budget.

sql:
SELECT total_yearly_compensation
FROM compensation_details
WHERE employee_id = 1;

external_knowledge:
- 'combined treasure chest' refers to the sum of stock grant values and bonuses;
- 'wise captains' refers to managers;
- 'vast eBay empire' refers to the company 'eBay'.

- 'seasoned professionals aged 30 and above' refers to employees who are 30 years or older;
- 'bustling hive of activity with more than 10 employees' refers to departments with more than 10 employees;
- 'ensuring that each department has at least three such seasoned veterans' means the department must have at least 3 employees aged 30 or above;
- 'ranked by the richness of their rewards' refers to ordering the results by the average yearly compensation in descending order.

- "Financially robust companies" refers to companies with high total revenue;
- "Generous employee compensation" refers to companies with high average yearly compensation;
- "Set up their headquarters" means the location where the company's main office is located.

- "seasoned leaders" refers to managers who have been with the company for at least five years;
- "tending to their plots" refers to being actively employed as a manager;
- "flourishing performance" refers to a performance rating greater than 4.5;
- "oversee more than five apprentices" refers to having more than five direct reports;
- "well-populated departments" refers to departments with a total number of employees.

- 'Most mature' refers to departments with the highest average employee age;
- 'Branches' are metaphorical representations of departments;
- 'Oldest and wealthiest' refers to the ordering by average age and cumulative compensation, both in descending order.
